g.text: Tips for Printing on Plastic
• Avoid printing anything on top of cut lines - the heat of the
laser reacts with the printed ink and can cause damage to
and peeling of the ink; place your cut lines at least 2 mm
away from any artwork to prevent heat damage to the ink.
Tips for Cutting Plastic
• Special considerations must be taken for plastic parts that
are intended to ﬁt together snugly without adhesive or
otherwise need above-average dimensional accuracy:
• Our laser’s kerf (cut width) is .015” (.37mm) total; .0075”
(.135mm) on either side of the cut line.
• 1/4” plastic’s thickness is .2195” ± .0305” (5.575mm ± .775mm).
• 1/8” plastic’s thickness is .1075” ± .0175” (2.731mm ± .444mm).
• All cut lines must be at least 1/8” apart.
• Line thickness does not affect the cut line. Lines
will be cut only down the center of any vector/line.
• Having lines cross could result in pieces becoming
disconnected.
• Check for duplicate vectors/lines directly on top of
each other. Duplicate lines result in a line being
cut twice which will affect edge quality and size.
• If you intend to glue parts together, avoid
cyanoacrylate glues as these will irreversibly haze
up the plastic. Use an acrylic welding compound
or an epoxy adhesive.
General Tips
Slug Line
The actual size of the plastic slug.
Safe Zone
Place all important text and artwork, and ALL cut
lines within the Safe Zone. Any cut lines beyond
the Safe Zone have the potential to compromise
the integrity of the plastic slug itself.
Nicks
To prevent your parts from falling out of the slug,
all cut lines should have at least 3 “nicks”. A nick
is a break in the cut line that keeps the piece
attached to the slug. The recommended nick size
is .01” (.25mm) for 1/8” acrylic and .005” (.125mm)
for 1/4” acrylic. Any pieces without nicks or with
undersized nicks WILL fall out of the slug and
potentially be lost, damaged, or be cut incorrectly.
Pieces with oversized nicks can chip when
punched out.
Registration
These red areas are where the slug is
physically registered to both the printer and the
laser. DO NOT place ANY text, artwork, or cut
lines on top of them. Putting artwork or cut
lines in this area will cause your design to be
manually rejected by our QA process. The gray
circles are holes in the slug - these will always
be cut out on any slug.
Cut Line
